JUANITA RONDON In my opinion, Inside Out is one of the best animated films I've ever seen. I really liked it because it's not only funny, but it also has a very profound message about emotions. Sometimes we think we should just be happy all the time, but this film shows that all emotions play an important role in our lives, even sadness. I thought it was really beautiful how, through Riley's story, we understand that feeling fear, anger, or sadness isn't wrong, and that sometimes we need to feel these things in order to learn, heal, and grow. I also loved how they depicted the human mind, with memories, personality islands, and the headquarters where emotions work. It was all very creative and helped me imagine how our feelings might work on the inside.

This film,while the story and concept is relatively simple on paper, the unique world and characters keep it interesting and it has sweet messages that can really resonate with an audience. I liked the personalities of the different emotions and the islands were very nice. Then the montages and memories of kid Riley really resonated with me and made me cry on a few occasions. The story of growing up,moving on and letting things go embodied by the story of Bing Bong and the fading memories was very powerful. That isn't even the main message,the main message is that sadness can be beneficial and necessary at times while too much optimism can be harmful at times as, but both are important. This film depicts that true joy can only be achieved through a mix of happy and sad moments and I like how that is reflected in Joy‚Äôs design. Her skin is gold but her hair is blue and her dress is a light green combination of the two (blue for sadness, gold for joy). I also just really like the trombone sound they use for sadness, at the beginning I thought that was worth mentioning. I also thought it was very realistic that in the stressful situations Riley copes with hostility,fear,and sarcasm. Then the last thing I want to touch on was how the family is betrayed in this film. I thought they found it a good job of portraying a healthy family dynamic that's realistic but also amusing to watch and is very supportive.

"Inside Out" is a vibrant, imaginative journey into the mind of an 11-year-old girl, where emotions take center stage. The film's unique concept and stunning animation are matched by its heartfelt storytelling. Joy, Sadness, Anger, Fear, and Disgust, each with their own distinct personalities, guide us through Riley's emotional landscape as she navigates a life-changing move. The film deftly balances humor and poignancy, exploring complex themes of loss, change, and the importance of embracing all emotions. "Inside Out" is a must-see for all ages, a touching reminder that even in the darkest of times, there is always a glimmer of hope.

Light hearted watch about the different emotions that go on inside each person. In this case, the main character was Riley, and we follow her as she grows into a young child. Her emotions grow chaotic when her family decides to move from Minnesota to San Francisco. In the end, the lesson learned is that all of the emotions are important, work together, and are valid. Her family supports her as she expresses how she misses Minnesota. But they don't move back. Inside a person, it's also cute how there are different islands/memories: family, friendship, goofiness, the sport you love, etc.

I'm not kidding when I say this movie changed my life forever. Given that, it easily is my favorite Pixar (and possibly just general) movie. As a 13 year old at the time of the movies release, I had gone through exactly the same situation as Riley about a year prior to this movie coming out. My family had a rough move that took a serious toll on my mental state. At the time of the move, I had a hard time dealing with the change in school, friends, and location. When this movie came out, I was interested, but wasn't sure what to fully expect going in. There were some differences in the situation, but as a 12 year old, they felt very similar. You don't know how to emotionally cope with this until later down the road. This movie became the pillar I would lean on to help train myself for the sad times. Without this film, I don't know if I would be the person I am today, or even if I would be around today. 100/10, cannot recommend enough.

This movie is beautifully crafted. The way that it dives into the complex world of emotions and how they shape our experiences and perceptions of the world is simple and yet deep. The animation is colorful and vibrant, grabbing your attention immediately. The voice acting is top-notch from all involved, with each person bringing the right amount of every emotion needed to be believable. Kaitlyn Dias is great as Riley, especially! The music from Michael Giacchino also perfectly fits and enhances everything within the film. In the realm of themes, the concept of artistically visualizing the brain as a huge functioning factory-style workplace is a unique and intriguing idea. The exploration of core memories and how they can be affected by our emotions adds an extra layer of depth to the film that many may appreciate. One of the standout aspects of Inside Out is the message that all emotions are important and necessary. It is a message for people of all ages. The film also touches on the idea that we all have our own inner worlds and experiences that others may not understand. Overall, it is a heartwarming and thought-provoking film that is sure to become a new all-time favorite for many.

‚ÄòInside Out' follows Riley, a young girl who has just moved to San Francisco with her parents. Leaving her life in Minnesota behind. She and her five core emotions, Joy, Anger, Sadness, Fear and Disgust, struggle to cope with her new life. I have a very sentimental attachment to this movie. I do believe it's one of the best films produced by Pixar so far. The emotional journey we see Riley go through in this movie, displayed in such creative ways is so touching. Transforming elements such as abstract thought and memory into a somewhat educational and effective format. Not only is the story and characters such a strong part of this movie, the animation and attention to detail is incredible. There is so much beautiful scenery and cinematography throughout the film. I couldn't recommend this movie enough! Whether it's to sit down with the family, or enjoying a quiet night in. This film is a must watch!

Inside Out, the 2015 animated film from Pixar, is an absolute cinematic masterpiece that captures the complexities of human emotions in a visually stunning and emotionally resonant way. Directed by Pete Docter, the film takes viewers on a journey through the mind of an 11-year-old girl named Riley, as her emotions - Joy, Sadness, Anger, Fear, and Disgust - navigate her life during a challenging period of transition. Here are several reasons why Inside Out is a masterpiece: Groundbreaking Concept: Inside Out presents a fresh and groundbreaking concept that delves into the inner workings of the human mind and explores the intricate world of emotions. The film personifies emotions as characters who operate in a control center, known as Headquarters, and their interactions and dynamics are brilliantly portrayed. The film's unique concept challenges conventional storytelling and provides an innovative and thought-provoking approach to depicting emotions on screen. Emotional Depth: Inside Out delves into the complexity of human emotions with remarkable depth and authenticity. It portrays how emotions are intertwined and how they shape our thoughts, memories, and actions. The film masterfully depicts the interplay of emotions, showing how Joy and Sadness are not mutually exclusive, but rather essential for each other's existence. The exploration of Sadness as a crucial emotion, often overlooked in society, is a groundbreaking approach that highlights the importance of embracing all emotions as part of the human experience. Visual Brilliance: The animation in Inside Out is visually breathtaking. Pixar's attention to detail is evident in every frame, creating a vibrant and immersive world that represents the inner workings of the mind. The creative use of color, lighting, and visual cues to represent different emotions and memories adds depth and richness to the storytelling. The stunning visuals enhance the emotional impact of the film, making it a truly cinematic experience. Relatable Storytelling: Inside Out tells a universal story that resonates with audiences of all ages. The film depicts the challenges of growing up, dealing with change, and navigating complex emotions in a relatable and heartfelt manner. It explores the struggles of adolescence, the importance of family and friendships, and the emotional journey we all go through as we mature. The story is presented in a way that is accessible to both children and adults, making it a film that can be appreciated by audiences of all generations. Memorable Characters: The characters in Inside Out are lovable, relatable, and memorable. Joy, Sadness, Anger, Fear, and Disgust are not just caricatures of emotions, but fully fleshed-out characters with their own personalities and motivations. Their interactions are both humorous and poignant, creating a deep emotional connection with the audience. The film's endearing characters are a testament to Pixar's ability to create multi-dimensional characters that resonate with audiences long after the credits roll. Impactful Themes: Inside Out delves into meaningful and impactful themes that are relevant to everyone. The film explores the importance of emotional intelligence, the need to acknowledge and embrace all emotions, and the value of memories and experiences in shaping our identities. It also delves into the complexity of mental health, highlighting the importance of taking care of our emotional well-being. These themes are handled with sensitivity and depth, making Inside Out a thought-provoking and introspective film that prompts meaningful conversations. Finally, Inside Out is a cinematic masterpiece that pushes the boundaries of storytelling and animation. Its groundbreaking concept, emotional depth, visual brilliance, relatable storytelling, memorable characters, and impactful themes make it a film that resonates with audiences on multiple levels. It is a testament to Pixar's storytelling prowess and their ability to create films that are not only entertaining but also thought-provoking and emotionally resonant. Inside Out is a must-watch for anyone!

Pixar's "Inside Out" is an original and emotionally gripping film that captivated audiences before its sequel. The movie offers a unique perspective by delving into the inner workings of a young girl's mind, personifying her emotions as characters. The relationship between Joy and Sadness is a central focus, as they embark on a journey together to not only comprehend each other but also to safeguard Riley from losing herself and her connections. The emotional rollercoaster they navigate, alongside Fear, Disgust, and Anger, provides a compelling exploration of the complexities of human emotions. The film skillfully portrays how memories are stored and the poignant adventure with Bing Bong adds depth to the storytelling. "Inside Out" is a heartwarming and entertaining experience suitable for families and children alike. It encourages collective engagement and fosters an understanding that it is natural to experience a range of emotions. Ultimately, the film conveys a powerful message that resonates with viewers of all ages - that it is acceptable to feel a variety of emotions, including anger and fear. "Inside Out" is a delightful and touching cinematic masterpiece that showcases the universality of human feelings.

A film created both for children and adults, which approaches psychological concepts in an outstandingly creative and accessible manner. The Fantasy, Animation, Comedy, Kids & Family movie ‚ÄòInside Out' (2015), directed by Pete Docter, finds an original way of depicting the processes our mind goes through during the times it is taken over by different emotions and memories. After freshly moving out with her family to San Francisco, 11-year-old protagonist Riley Andersen, whose mind is controlled by 5 basic emotions: Joy, Sadness, Fear, Disgust, and Anger, is having a hard time getting accustomed to the new environment, thus longing for the old days and bringing back the bittersweet memories of her birthplace. This, however, means that the lead in the Brain Headquarters would be taken by Sadness, which is seen negatively by the other emotions, especially Joy, who took the leader role. In her attempt of getting Sadness to step back from the control panel, the both end up sucked out of the Headquarters, accompanying Riley's core memories, which they now have to find a way to restore, in order to keep Riley's personality, all while Anger, Fear, and Disgust are forced to take charge of Riley's life, with disastrous results. What I mostly liked about the movie was the writing, which was done very accurately to portray how emotions and memories help make us who we are. The team managed to illustrate Joy as the most complex emotion, envisioning her as vulnerable and intangible because she was "unapologetically positive". They had the idea about Joy's potential to excessively manipulate youth, creating Riley's "social storms", which is an excellent way of addressing toxic positivity. The key-message that is highlighted throughout the events in the film is that happiness implies feeling sadness as well. Loving someone intrinsically means feeling hurt when we lose them. We NEED sadness in our lives, in order to fully experience joy. We need to cope with painful situations from time to time, in order to grow and become better as a person. ("Crying Helps Me Slow Down And Obsess Over The Weight Of Life's Problems." - Sadness) Another great aspect of the movie is its animation, particularly the character design. The team had been assigned a hard job of visualising and turning abstract concepts into understandable for kids animated characters. Not only have they given every character a unique colour and shape pattern (with Anger being shaped like a brick, Joy - a star, Sadness - a teardrop and Fear being tall and thin like a nerve), but they totally moulded each of the emotions from different textures, as well as even making their moves different, accordingly to their personalities (making Fear to be all floppy and dangling all the time and Anger to always keep his stiff, still posture). On top of that, they even went as far as making Joy glow from within, by creating a "sparkly" aura for her, which took a lot of time and efforts. All in all, I can admit that having watched the animation more than 3 times doesn't make rewatching it every time any less of a tear-jerker. It is hands down a brilliant production, put together for both children and their parents to enjoy. I absolutely recommend it for a family movie night, not only because it's a much simple way of teaching a child about how their mind works, but also because it's a great tool to help people of any age understand themselves more and learn how to figure out their emotions and besides, it offers some great insight into psychology and neuroscience in a highly uncomplicated way.

Pixar has made movies of all kinds - What if toys had feelings, what if insects had feelings, what if monsters had feelings, what if cars had feelings, what if fishes had feelings, what if rats had feelings. And now they have made Inside Out - what if feelings had feelings? Inside Out is probably one of the most underrated movies that Pixar has made. It was the first original Pixar movie which I didn't get to know about when it released (the first such one was a sequel, Monsters University), and I'm really surprised how this movie gets overlooked so easily. The way I see it, this movie is a social commentary about how we perceive life with our emotions. Riley here is a metaphor of us, how we feel when we move to a new place and are unable to handle the new life. In such situations we either feel scared, angry or depressed. When Riley starts crying in class, Joy tries to stop Sadness from ruining her memory with a vacuum but ends up destroying all her other memories. This is another metaphor from our lives, where we end up forgetting all our happy memories in times of desperation. Later on Joy and Sadness are in her memories, where they see Riley's childhood drawing of Bing Bong whom she considered her friend. The plot has been made with a complete sense of nostalgia. When we feel nostalgic, we feel both happiness and sadness at the same time. We are happy because we got to live those times, the time which was better than what we are living at the moment. We are sad because we know that time never stops, and so everyday we are straying further away from when it happened. We will never be able to live the day again, and it shall only stay in our memory. While Joy and Sadness are not present Fear, Anger and Disgust control her. I don't think I need to explain this. Riley has lost all her happiness and does not feel any sadness. Keep in mind she had previously cried in class, which is something very embarrassing for a ten year old child. As a result she does not want to show her sorrow in front of everyone since she fears people will laugh at her, so instead she tries to cover it with anger and disgust. This is just like how we behave when we are depressed but are also too afraid of what others might think if they learn about it. And then there is the memory dump, the place where the old memories are forgotten. This is one of the deepest messages that the movie gave us. To save Joy and Sadness and allow them to get out of the pit, Bing Bong readily sacrifices himself. This is because he had always considered himself and Riley friends, and he was ready to sacrifice his own life for this. It also shows how Riley has now lost the memory of Bing Bong due to her depression and frustration, and it is something she will never remember again. This is a metaphor of how we forget the small details from our childhood which gave us joy once we grow out of the phase. It also symbolises that although Bing Bong has been lost forever, Riley's joy and sadness will always remember him. This is similar to how we get nostalgic whenever we see our childhood writings and drawings. And finally when Joy and Sadness do make it back, then Joy chooses to let Sadness guide Riley. If she wanted she could have guided Riley and make her feel happy about reuniting with her parents. But in that case the moment would have completely lost the impact. So instead Sadness did it, which is why Riley started crying, something she had not done for a long time. This is yet another metaphor of when we are unable to hold our sorrow for too long and burst out crying. As a result her parents are finally able to understand the situation she is in and give her more love. In the end Riley starts feeling happy, since everyone has understood the value of Joy. She was the first emotion that Riley felt, and the one who guided them all in the time of desperation. All the other emotions came to her afterwards, which is why they are not as emotionally attached to Riley as Joy does. Joy knows what is the best for her, just like how we feel the best thing for our life is what makes us happy.

Just‚Ä¶.how? How did Pixar make another flawless film after three films that I would either consider meh or bad? I just don't get it! Finally, how can you not talk about this movie without mentioning the ending, with two big emotional parts that really leave a huge impact. The first being the death of Bing Bong, which feels a little like it comes out of nowhere, but you're going to remember it. But that's minor, and no one is going to be thinking that in their first viewing, I only noticed it in my most previous viewing of the movie anyway. I really think someone should do a deeper dive into this movie, cause it really deserves it. However, I can only praise it for so long. Inside Out review A heartfelt animated movie, "Inside Out", takes you on a rollercoaster of emotions with creative imagination and a look back at some nostalgic moments we might have had in our childhood. Unlike any other, Pixar studios created an original movie of the emotions that go behind a person's mind and made them into having their own personalities. Focused on the mind of a little girl ,Riley her life is shown as typically any perfect childhood. With the presence of the emotion joy it shows her story of her two loving parents raising her and living the life with many moments that one child creates. Including the building of humor, friendship and playing your favorite sport. But as all children go through the other emotions such as sadness, fear ,disgust and anger it will include her experiences. However, her life takes a sudden turn when she has to move with her parents from their hometown Minnesota to San Francisco. Her emotions will be put to the test in adapting to a new lifestyle they're typically unused to. To start off , it shows the beginning of the first years in Riley's life. Transitioning from stages to the preteens years of her life. This is where she experiences many emotions and personal likeness and dislikeness. Riley is seen on her journey as she experiences all typical childhood memories. From learning how to walk to talking your first new words. Discovering your least favorite meal to favorite toy to take with you everywhere. The laughter you create and the sad moments you experience. The rewarding moments of receiving a good grade to being upset for losing an important game. As Riley is growing she has experienced majority exciting emotions until a certain news comes to her attention. She will be moving from her childhood home Minnesota, where she was born, raised, and grew up to miles away into the city of San Francisco. Despite the change , her emotion Joy makes Riley see all this in a positive way. Meeting new friends, decorating a new room and many more ideas. Arriving at the new location, Riley is quick to notice the drastic change in seeing her new home. Adapting to the city and less outdoor activity is one of the unfortunate changes making her find new adventures. On her first day of school, she is introduced to her classmates and told to talk a bit more from her time back home. As she recalls some of her favorite memories, the emotion sadness touches her favorite memory, changing Riley's memory to a sad moment and turning it into a sorrowful memory. Joy continues to try and make Riley enjoy the new memories. After they had another similar disagreement Joy and Sadness cause the core memories to be knocked from their containers and accidentally vacuumed along with them into Riley's emotional interior. With this problem, it leaves the other emotions Fear, Disgust and Anger to run the emotions until the others return changing RIleys behavior. Throughout the film it shows the many obstacles and challenges Joy and Sadness must go through to reach the headquarters. Following with revisiting old memories and lifelong imaginary friends. It will take a spin through some future glimpse some being Riley's future boyfriend and many more. Overall this unfortunate event turned out to be a better lesson. The emotions appreciating each other's teamwork to help Riley have the best life she could as she grows up. Enjoying the moments one creates as living life with a positive attitude.

Pretty fantastic. The specific look of the characters ran from the familiar (humans, Bing Bong) to the unique, fresh. Colors are extreme, but in a good way. This is comedy, but it's not all just a light-hearted ride. And it's the heavier elements of the story that make this such a fully-realized take on the base concepts here. Riley moves with her family half way across the country, to a place far different from her Minnesota hometown; too different, it would seem. Stellar work by the voice-over cast. Poehler is always great. Smart choice in casting Smith as Sadness. She knows her way around some sad, as she clearly showed on The Office. Kind was a great Bing Bong. Kaling was all over Disgust. And Hader was....well...Hader; which means brilliant and funny and just unbeatable. The movie does tread a bit close to overly sweet at moments, but it never gets too saccharine, sentimental or dark. There's a wonderful balance between the emotions that show the very real feelings of a kid going through such changes. Overt sweetness that is typical in kids animation is sorta replaced with nostalgia; a common but strong emotion. But along with the fantastical, the eye candy visuals, the depth and cleverness of the screenplay, they always remember to bring the funny. 4 stars

The score was awesome & the voice acting was among the best that I've ever seen as the casting choices were absolutely impeccable. I found the pixellated aura around Joy & the others to be rather distracting but mostly because it seemed like the rest of the film was very finely animated & ended up with an internal debate over whether they were supposed to seem like they were fading away or not; also, knowing that hair is among the hardest things to animate, I found Joy's immobile hair a bit lacking in nuance. The personality islands stretched my suspension of disbelief a bit & I can imagine retrospectively them going a different direction with the screenplay in the form of the emotions conquering some sort of antagonist made up of the outburst Riley seemed destined for over the move, but I digress. The movie was still very good viewing material exactly how it was. Kudos!

The parallel of internal struggle and outward reaction to adversity really sets this movie apart. The audience is literally taken on a exploration of the mind, and the story is not only fun, but capable of serious philosophical concepts. Because it exemplifies "show, don't tell" those conversations are compacted into palatable actions by the characters. This is a movie that might make you laugh, cry or both. It's hard to believe that someone wouldn't relate to this somehow, and probably more that they wouldn't enjoy it at all.

Inside Out, originated by Pete Docter & Ronnie del Carmen, put out the most unique & fresh story premise since Toy Story in 1995! With Docter directing, del Carmen screenwriting, & Andrew Stanton & John Lasseter producing, they brought back the Pixar hype, coming off the mediocre titles in Brave, Monsters University & The Good Dinosaur. The concept is very creative & original, with a very clever narrative. The story was very well paced, touching up on real world problems, hitting many emotional notes. For a children's film, it is very mature, while still having great family fun. For a fictional tale, this film really made you think after the movie; I'd be lying if I said I never thought about this in my head. The characters were just a blast of fun, with everyone having their own definitive personalities, of course. Our master child if you will, had great real life problems. Her character really reflects on what it's like at that age, and what your emotions feel at most times. If Pete Docter & Ronnie del Carmen wanted to get real crazy, they could've added emotions like, love, loyalty, caring, etc, but they would've had to re-write the whole narrative for that to work. I got myself so invested into Sadness, that I built this real-life hate for her. The screenplay by Ronnie del Carmen, Josh Cooley & Meg LeFauve had plenty of solid laughs, incorporating deep dialogues, speaking about mature, real world issues. It truly goes without say, the cinematography & animations are just as close to flawless as it gets. Everything had amazing detail, being either vibrant or dull while showing great texture. The production designer in Ralph Eggleston created this outside the box world, incorporating terrific set pieces. Overall, I didn't really find to much wrong with this film, other than it being a little slower at times, and it kind of copied that Toy Story feel a little; nevertheless very solid Pixar film, to show that they're back in action, while winning an Academy Award for Best Animated Feature Film.

The question of whether an animated film ostensibly made for an audience of children can gain legitimacy on the level of a dramatic film made for an audience of adults was essentially answered by this film which was a resounding critical and commercial success. It is heartwarming without pushing emotional responses on the audience and provides children and adults with an important message about the nature of our emotions and the need to balance them. Like most Pixar films it has the added benefit of looking great and featuring voice performances from famous movie stars who would actually seem to be trying. Any parent looking to entertain their child for an hour and a half could do much worse than this lovely film that blended mass appeal with deeply personal touches. What really helps the film is that the emotional arc that our apparently perfect main character Joy, Amy Poehler, goes on is effective and ends in a climax that makes her entire journey feel necessary. The realization that experiencing the highs and the lows is important so we can appreciate how special it is to be happy and learn from moments in which we felt sad. Our feelings mirror Joy's feelings as Sadness,, does come across as incredibly annoying at the beginning of the film but we come to realize that she is necessary by the end of the film and her acceptance is a nice moment. She is in many ways like the outcast kid who is slightly less boisterous and extroverted than her schoolmates and surely children will be able to identify with both Joy and Sadness as they realize they each play crucial roles. This is true of anything in life as whether you are running a company or simply being part of your family you are one cog in a larger machine that needs several different people to make it work. Joy and Sadness make each other better and work together for a common goal instead of knocking each other down due to their different ideas and completely destroying the life of the human they work for. These are the sort of selfless and giving figures that young women and men should model themselves on and Pixar should be applauded for making a film that is truly family friendly.
